1. Cargo manifest

The Cargo.toml is very small, but it tells you a lot about the intended shape of the system.

Why these dependencies matter

serde and serde_json
These signal that the system wants serializable protocol objects. Even though the scaffold does not yet define a final binary wire format, it is already structured as if messages, constitutions, and VM programs need to be serialized, stored, transmitted, and replayed.

sha2 and hex
These tell you the system’s identity and commitment logic is hash-first. Objects are identified by digests, braid membership is commit-friendly, and knot formation is root-oriented.

thiserror
This is a practical but important sign: the scaffold wants explicit, typed failure domains. That is aligned with deterministic replay and bounded failure semantics.

chrono
TXXMs and knots are already timestamped. Even though final protocol timing rules are not fully defined here, the scaffold is already assuming wall-clock metadata exists alongside chain/block anchoring.

So the manifest is small, but it is already encoding a worldview: structured, serializable, hash-committed, replayable protocol objects with typed errors.

