3. hash.rs: the commitment substrate

This is the simplest module, but it is foundational.

It defines:
	•	Hash32 as the standard 32-byte digest type,
	•	sha256(data) for hashing,
	•	hash_pair(a, b) for internal pair hashing,
	•	merkle_root(leaves) for root commitment,
	•	hex32(h) for readable hex display.

Why this matters

Kapnet, as you’ve been describing it, needs many layers of digestibility:
	•	message IDs,
	•	braid commitments,
	•	knot headers,
	•	state roots,
	•	weakwork subject bindings,
	•	possibly future constitution IDs and proof objects.

This module establishes the minimal cryptographic grammar for that.

Important design choice

The merkle logic duplicates the last node on odd cardinalities, which is the standard practical approach for many Merkle constructions. So the scaffold is implicitly assuming batchable root commitments for collections of hashes.

What it does not yet do

It does not yet include:
	•	domain separation,
	•	tagged hashing,
	•	double-SHA or configurable digest families,
	•	proof generation and proof verification,
	•	sparse Merkle or accumulator variants.

So right now it is enough to make the rest of the scaffold coherent, but not enough to finalize protocol-grade commitment formats.

