4. txxm.rs: the message primitive

This is one of the most important modules in the whole scaffold.

It defines the core message object: Txxm.

Main components

Destination
A TXXM can target:
	•	Room(String)
	•	Guild(String)
	•	Federation(String)
	•	Direct([u8; 32])
	•	Broadcast

This is already quite important conceptually. It means routing is not just “to an address.” It is semantic routing across social and governance scopes.

That aligns extremely well with the Kapnet idea that messages are not only transport events but typed coordination events.

TxxmFlags
The flags include:
	•	has_script
	•	encrypted
	•	requires_pow
	•	high_priority
	•	checkpoint_candidate

These are simple booleans right now, but they already partition messages into protocol classes.

For example:
	•	has_script implies executable semantics,
	•	requires_pow implies relay admission pressure,
	•	checkpoint_candidate implies knot relevance.

So the flags are already serving as a tiny policy-control plane.

WeakworkRef
This references:
	•	algorithm,
	•	nonce,
	•	target leading zero bits.

This is not yet a full proof object embedded in the TXXM, but it provides a header-level linkage to weakwork.

TxxmHeader
This includes:
	•	version,
	•	optional txid_hint,
	•	sender public key bytes,
	•	timestamp,
	•	nonce,
	•	destination list,
	•	flags,
	•	optional weakwork reference,
	•	tags map.

This is already a strong shape. It suggests that a message is:
versioned, attributable, timestamped, route-aware, policy-aware, optionally work-gated, and extensible via tags.

Txxm
The full object contains:
	•	header,
	•	body,
	•	optional script,
	•	optional signature.

This is a strong design choice. It means the message envelope and body are separate from script execution material. That allows future separation between:
	•	human-readable payload,
	•	machine-executable payload,
	•	authorization material.

⸻

Canonical hashing

The most important logic here is:
	•	unsigned_digest()
	•	id()

unsigned_digest() deterministically serializes the message fields into bytes and hashes them.

id() then hashes the unsigned digest together with the signature if present.

Why this is good

This gives you a stable pre-signing digest and a post-signing object ID. That is useful for:
	•	signing workflows,
	•	deduplication,
	•	weakwork subject binding,
	•	message identity after authentication.

Why this is not finished

The current encoding is custom and internal. It is consistent enough for the scaffold, but not yet production-grade.

It still needs:
	•	a formal canonical encoding spec,
	•	field ordering guarantees across versions,
	•	domain-separated tags,
	•	normalization rules,
	•	exact signature preimage definitions,
	•	a standard for script hashing and witness separation.

But as a scaffold, it is already quite good. It shows the direction clearly.

