5. weakwork.rs: lightweight admission work

This module defines WeakworkClaim.

A claim contains:
	•	subject: what is being worked on,
	•	route_hint,
	•	relay_hint,
	•	nonce,
	•	leading_zero_bits.

What this means conceptually

This is a local, message-bound work proof. It is not base-chain mining. It is not chain consensus. It is more like:

“I spent some effort to make this message more eligible for transport and ordering.”

That is extremely aligned with the Kapnet idea of pre-settlement cyphereconomic structuring of traffic.

Main methods

digest()
Hashes the subject plus hints plus nonce plus target threshold.

This binds the work claim not just to a message but also to a route context.

That is subtle and good: weakwork can become topologically meaningful, not merely computationally meaningful.

score()
Counts leading zero bits in the digest.

is_valid()
Checks whether the score meets the claimed threshold.

for_txxm(...)
Creates a default weakwork claim from a TXXM, using its unsigned digest as subject.

This is very sensible. It means the work is bound to the content being forwarded, not to some arbitrary detached token.

mine(max_iters)
A brute-force loop for finding a valid nonce.

This is obviously just a demonstrator, but it is enough to simulate the weakwork lifecycle.

⸻

Why this module is important

It is the first place where Kapnet stops looking like “messages plus structs” and starts looking like an ordered market for message inclusion.

Weakwork is what gives relays a nontrivial admission surface.

What is still missing
	•	no multiple algorithms,
	•	no weighted price curve,
	•	no expiration or time decay,
	•	no anti-replay tags,
	•	no reusable work pools,
	•	no subscription-tier overrides,
	•	no route market clearing,
	•	no shared weakwork combining logic.

So this is still a simple PoW-like gate, but it already captures the direction.

