6. braid.rs: the coordination DAG

This module is where the scaffold gets genuinely interesting.

It defines:
	•	BraidEntry
	•	Braid

BraidEntry

A braid entry contains:
	•	id
	•	parents
	•	txxm
	•	optional weakwork
	•	local_weight

This means every accepted message can become a node in a local DAG-like coordination structure.

Weight model

local_weight = 1 + weakwork_score

That is simple, but it already encodes an ordering idea:
	•	every message gets baseline inclusion weight,
	•	stronger weakwork makes it heavier.

Braid

This stores entries in a map and supports:
	•	insertion,
	•	tip detection,
	•	cumulative weight calculation,
	•	heaviest tip selection,
	•	Merkle commitment,
	•	digest summarization.

⸻

Why this is structurally important

This is the first strong embodiment of your repeated braid/knot language.

Instead of a plain queue or mempool, messages are organized into a causally branchable structure.

That enables future behaviors like:
	•	competing sequences,
	•	localized conflict resolution,
	•	checkpoint candidate selection,
	•	replay of coordination flow,
	•	topological rather than purely temporal ordering.

Tips logic

The tips() function returns entries that are not referenced as parents by others.

In effect, the braid maintains a frontier.

Heaviest tip logic

heaviest_tip() picks the tip with maximum cumulative ancestry weight.

This is not yet a perfect protocol fork-choice rule, but it is already a useful placeholder for:
	•	local preference,
	•	checkpoint proposal ordering,
	•	relay prioritization.

Important caveat

The cumulative-weight recursion sums over parents. In a DAG with shared ancestry, naive recursive accumulation can count shared ancestors multiple times depending on structure. As a scaffold this is fine, but for protocol correctness this will need more precise semantics.

Still, as a placeholder, it tells you the intended direction very clearly:
Kapnet wants weighted DAG preference, not just FIFO relay order.

