9. vm.rs: bounded deterministic execution

This is another core module.

It defines a small KScript-like VM.

Value

Supported value types:
	•	U64
	•	I64
	•	Bool
	•	Bytes
	•	Text
	•	Hash
	•	Role

This is a deliberately small typed value set. It is not general-purpose computing. It is enough for deterministic policy and light state transforms.

Op

Supported instructions include:
	•	flow/control basics: Nop, Halt, Abort
	•	stack ops: Push, Dup, Drop
	•	logic: Eq, Not, And, Or
	•	arithmetic: Add, Sub
	•	byte manipulation: Concat, Sha256
	•	state interaction: Load, Store
	•	enforcement: Require(bool)

This is exactly what a minimal constitutional machine should look like. Not Turing-complete. Not fancy. Just enough to evaluate and mutate bounded state.

Program

Contains:
	•	version
	•	max_steps
	•	list of ops

The max_steps bound is absolutely the right instinct. It directly enforces bounded execution.

VmContext

Holds variables.

VmResult

Returns:
	•	halted status,
	•	step count,
	•	resulting stack,
	•	resulting variables.

VmError

Includes explicit deterministic failure modes:
	•	step limit exceeded,
	•	stack underflow,
	•	type mismatch,
	•	missing variable,
	•	explicit abort,
	•	require failed.

This is excellent for replay and verification.

⸻

Execution model

The execute() function runs opcodes sequentially until:
	•	Halt,
	•	end of program,
	•	or an error.

The program is bounded by max_steps, which means no infinite execution.

Why this is very Kapnet-compatible

A coordination VM should be:
	•	deterministic,
	•	bounded,
	•	inspectable,
	•	replayable,
	•	small enough to reason about.

This VM already does that.

What it still lacks
	•	no jump/branching model,
	•	no external call discipline,
	•	no resource classes beyond step count,
	•	no typed memory regions,
	•	no proofs of noninterference,
	•	no serialization standard for programs,
	•	no privilege-aware execution context,
	•	no state delta output format.

So it is a small kernel, but a useful one.

