The hidden architecture underneath the code

Even though the code is simple, the scaffold already implies a fairly strong system model.

Layer 1: message layer

TXXM is the transport and semantic envelope.

Layer 2: admission layer

Weakwork determines whether a relay should spend attention and storage on the message.

Layer 3: ordering layer

Accepted messages are inserted into a braid with weight.

Layer 4: governance layer

Rooms, guilds, roles, constitutions, and membership gates shape where messages can land.

Layer 5: execution layer

Scripts can be embedded and executed in a deterministic bounded VM.

Layer 6: checkpoint layer

Braids and resulting state can be summarized into knot claims.

That is already very much a Kapnet kernel.

⸻

The strongest parts of the scaffold

A few things are particularly strong, even at this early stage.

1. The separation of concerns is good

Messages, work, ordering, governance, execution, state, and relay policy are separate modules. That gives you room to evolve each independently.

2. Bounded determinism is present

The VM is not pretending to be general-purpose. That is the right instinct.

3. Governance is first-class

Constitutions are not comments or metadata. They are hashable program-adjacent objects.

4. Knot headers already look real

The knot object is much closer to a real protocol artifact than many early scaffolds get.

5. The relay workflow is coherent

This is not just a pile of structs. The ingest pipeline actually makes sense.

